<subsection xml:id="subsec-appropriate-scale-for-a-linear-equation">
    <title>appropriate scale for a linear equation</title>

    <p>
        When plotting a linear equation on a Cartesian plane,        
    </p>
    <p>
        choosing the right scale is important to ensure that all points fit on the graph and are evenly spaced for easy interpretation.
    </p>
    <p>
        The scale refers to how numbers are represented on the x-axis and y-axis.
    </p>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{red} \textbf{Work in groups}}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            The table shows the table of values for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> for the linear equation <m>\textbf{y = 2x + 3}</m>
        </p>
        <p>
            <ol marker="(a).">
                <li>
                    
                    <tabular halign="left" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium" width="auto" >
                        <row>
                            <cell>x</cell>                    
                            <cell>-2</cell>                
                            <cell>-1</cell>
                            <cell>0</cell>
                            <cell>1</cell>
                            <cell>2</cell>
                            
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>y</cell>
                            <cell>?</cell>
                            <cell>?</cell>
                            <cell>?</cell>
                            <cell>?</cell>
                            <cell><m>7</m></cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Complete the table above for the linear equation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Plot the points on a Cartesian coordinate system
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Join the points on a straight line
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Discuss and compare your work with other groups
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>{\color{red} \textbf{Learning Points}}</m>
    </p>
    <p>
        In a Cartesian coordinate system, a straight line can be used to symbolise a linear equation.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                consider the Linear equation <m>\textbf{y} = -\frac{\textbf{1}}{\textbf{2}}x + \textbf{4}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(a).">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            From the Linear equation, fill the following table
                        </p>
                        <tabular halign="left" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium" width="auto" >
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>                    
                                <cell><m>-4</m></cell>                
                                <cell><m>-2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>0</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                                
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>y</m></cell>
                                <cell>?</cell>
                                <cell>?</cell>
                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                                <cell>?</cell>
                                <cell>?</cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            From the table,plot the points for corresponding values of x and y on a Cartesian plane.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            Using a straight line join the points
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                <ol marker="(i).">
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            The complete table is
                        </p>
                        <tabular halign="left" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium" width="auto">
                            <row>
                                <cell><m>x</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>Calculation</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>\textbf{y Value}</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>-4</cell>
                                <cell><m>\textbf{y} = -\frac{\textbf{1}}{\textbf{2}}(-4) + \textbf{4} = 2 + 4 =\textbf{6}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>6</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>-2</cell>
                                <cell><m>\textbf{y} = -\frac{\textbf{1}}{\textbf{2}}(-2) + \textbf{4} = 1 + 4 =\textbf{5}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>5</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>0</cell>
                                <cell><m>\textbf{y} = -\frac{\textbf{1}}{\textbf{2}}(0) + \textbf{4} = 0 + 4 =\textbf{4}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>4</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>2</cell>
                                <cell><m>\textbf{y} = -\frac{\textbf{1}}{\textbf{2}}(2) + \textbf{4} = -1 + 4 =\textbf{3}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>3</m></cell>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <cell>4</cell>
                                <cell><m>\textbf{y} = -\frac{\textbf{1}}{\textbf{2}}(4) + \textbf{4} = -2 + 4 =\textbf{2}</m></cell>
                                <cell><m>2</m></cell>
                            </row>
                        </tabular>

                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <image>
                            <latex-image label="l">
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                                                % Draw grid
                                \draw[very thin,gray!50] (-5,-2) grid (5,7);
                                
                                % Draw x and y axes
                                \draw[thick,->] (-5.5,0) -- (5.5,0) node[anchor=north] {\textbf{x}};
                                \draw[thick,->] (0,-2.5) -- (0,7.5) node[anchor=east] {\textbf{y}};
                                
                                % Tick marks and labels
                                \foreach \x in {-4,-2,2,4} {  % Removed redundant 0 on x-axis
                                    \draw[thick] (\x,-0.15) -- (\x,0.15);
                                    \node[anchor=north] at (\x,-0.3) {\textbf{\x}};
                                }

                                \foreach \y in {-2,2,4,6} {  % Removed redundant 0 on y-axis
                                    \draw[thick] (-0.15,\y) -- (0.15,\y);
                                    \node[anchor=east] at (-0.3,\y) {\textbf{\y}};
                                }

                                % Single origin label
                                \node[anchor=north east] at (-0.1,-0.1) {\textbf{0}};

                                % Plot points (without labels)
                                \fill[red] (-4,6) circle (3pt);
                                \fill[blue] (-2,5) circle (3pt);
                                \fill[green] (0,4) circle (3pt);
                                \fill[orange] (2,3) circle (3pt);
                                \fill[purple] (4,2) circle (3pt);

                                % Draw the line connecting the points
                                \draw[thick,blue] (-4,6) -- (4,2);
                                
                                % Equation of the line
                                \node[blue] at (1.5,2.5) {$y = -\frac{1}{2}x + 4$};
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                            </latex-image>
                            
                        </image>
                    </li>
                </ol>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    
</subsection>